 Update 2018-04-05
 &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="callout-content"&gt;&lt;p&gt;official docs are now also online at




&lt;a href="https://doc-snapshots.qt.io/qtforpython/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"&gt;https://doc-snapshots.qt.io/qtforpython/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Standalone PySide2 wheels</title><link>https://markholloway.com/blog/2018/02/20/standalone-pyside2-wheels/</link><pubDate>Tue, 20 Feb 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://markholloway.com/blog/2018/02/20/standalone-pyside2-wheels/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;The Qt Company has yet to release official, standalone and pip-installable
PySide2 wheels. However, since they made it possible to build standalone wheels
successfully, I&amp;rsquo;m now building such unofficial, standalone wheels here using
free CI services (thanks 



&lt;a href="https://travis-ci.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"&gt;Travis&lt;/a&gt; and




